<span id="freeTextContainer4935560349350260891">Max Weber explores the religious psychology of Protestant Christianity during the 16th-19th centuries and its role in the development of capitalism.<br/><br/>Excellent work of scholarship that musters information from many disciplines. I understand why this is considered such an interesting and important work of scholarship. The depth of insight he offers makes me want to investigate the sources he cites further. He dances between philosophy, theology, historical accounts, labor statistics, etc in a pleas</span>
  <span id="freeText4935560349350260891" style="display:none">Max Weber explores the religious psychology of Protestant Christianity during the 16th-19th centuries and its role in the development of capitalism.<br /><br />Excellent work of scholarship that musters information from many disciplines. I understand why this is considered such an interesting and important work of scholarship. The depth of insight he offers makes me want to investigate the sources he cites further. He dances between philosophy, theology, historical accounts, labor statistics, etc in a pleasant way. If you are interested in capitalism and want to learn more about its development I’d highly recommend.<br /><br />My only complaint is that the ideas Weber had weren’t developed further during his life. His rebuttals to critique included at the end largely reiterate his previous arguments.</span>
