    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3695577411" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3695577411" />
    <a title="Sooho Lee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22206815-sooho-lee"><img alt="Sooho Lee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610439784p2/22206815.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3695577411?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sooho Lee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sooho Lee" href="/user/show/22206815-sooho-lee">Sooho Lee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780415254069" href="/book/show/435817.The_Protestant_Ethic_and_the_Spirit_of_Capitalism">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22206815-sooho-lee?shelf=sociology">sociology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22206815-sooho-lee?shelf=economics">economics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22206815-sooho-lee?shelf=theology">theology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22206815-sooho-lee?shelf=important-reads">important-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3695577411" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14207532406704247996">The first time I heard the term &quot;Protestant work ethic&quot; was when a coworker guessed why the managers particularly liked the new hires from a private Christian school: &quot;I think it&apos;s because we work hard, and working hard without being told feels like a moral thing.&quot; I don&apos;t think she read Max Weber, but she kind of nails it. <br/><br/>The second time, and the real impetus to hear straight from the horse&apos;s mouth, was because of my favorite theologian and her &quot;Christianity and the New Spirit of Capitalism&quot; (</span>
  <span id="freeText14207532406704247996" style="display:none">The first time I heard the term "Protestant work ethic" was when a coworker guessed why the managers particularly liked the new hires from a private Christian school: "I think it's because we work hard, and working hard without being told feels like a moral thing." I don't think she read Max Weber, but she kind of nails it. <br /><br />The second time, and the real impetus to hear straight from the horse's mouth, was because of my favorite theologian and her "Christianity and the New Spirit of Capitalism" (Yale University Press, 2019). Based on the back endorsement, I thought Kathryn Tanner was going to rip apart Max Weber -- she didn't. In fact (I might be reading her wrong, so I want to read it again), she sort of admires the insight of Weber's analysis. She doesn't like it; she disagrees with Weber's core tenants of Protestant faith and ethics; but she does not harangue it.<br /><br />I approached Max Weber with the same attitude, and I can see why Tanner was more careful and nuanced than I had initially assumed. Weber confines his analysis to a particular branches of Protestantism and of capitalism. He peppers his summaries and analyses with phrases like "for our limited purposes...," "this incomplete but enough to see that...," "obviously, this is not true for all ___..." He's not trying to make a programmatic, prescriptive work ("Protestants should do x, y, z because of their beliefs") but a limited description ("Protestants have these practices and rational that produce x, y, z practices"). And it's best to read "The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism" that way. <br /><br />I like Weber's analysis. He doesn't condemn wealth or acquisition. He doesn't think greed is the defining feature of capitalism (agreed) but the practice to reinvest into capital for future production. He doesn't condemn nor praise the Protestant work ethic. He was curious why modern capitalism flourished in communities rooted in certain branches of Protestantism, and certainly not in Catholicism. In other words, why were the Puritans and Puritan-based communities with figures like Benjamin Franklin so in-tuned with the spirit of capitalism? Granted, He's not a theologian, so his caricature of Puritans and Calvinists, though at once funny and scary, is narrow. But that's not his main concern: he doesn't care that this kind of theology produces these kinds of practices (abstaining from worldly indulgences and reinvesting into capital for further and better production). <br /><br />Tanner is a theologian (par excellence), so her exposition on the Protestant faith is superb. And in some sense, she reverses Weber's analysis. Instead of starting with the uniqueness of Protestant (Puritanical or Calvinistic) faith and connect it to the explosion of modern capitalism, Tanner starts with finance-dominated capitalism as its own world, or how Weber in the end describes capitalism as "the iron cage," with its own ethics, anthropology, and even theology, whose god is the Market. Then she offers a "Protestant anti-work ethic" to combat the iron cage. <br /><br />(note: Weber is talking about industrial capitalism -- the production of goods for economy commerce; Kathryn Tanner focuses on the "new" spirit of capitalism, what she calls "finance-dominated capitalism," which obsesses over capital gain, loans, stocks, and debt; whether they are one and the same thing is up to the reader, but I don't think they are, and Tanner makes that distinction in her book).</span>
  <a data-text-id="14207532406704247996" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


