        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer718666382" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13083234326196810221">This review concerns the Norton Critical Edition of Weber&apos;s work. The Protestant Ethic is a dramatic, seductive, original work that, despite its controversial premise, deserves an edition such as this. The edition employs the classic 1930 Parsons translation along with the translator&apos;s preface. <br/><br/>The text is left almost entirely unchanged. The editor occasionally modifies a footnote to clarify a cross reference or explain a foreign phrase left untranslated. A glossary of key terms or controversial</span>
  <span id="freeText13083234326196810221" style="display:none">This review concerns the Norton Critical Edition of Weber's work. The Protestant Ethic is a dramatic, seductive, original work that, despite its controversial premise, deserves an edition such as this. The edition employs the classic 1930 Parsons translation along with the translator's preface. <br /><br />The text is left almost entirely unchanged. The editor occasionally modifies a footnote to clarify a cross reference or explain a foreign phrase left untranslated. A glossary of key terms or controversially translated phrases would have been a nice complement to this volume, though the editor's preface directs the reader to some literature that discusses issues of translation.<br /><br />Five essays follow the text, all of which are remarkably useful. One examines Weber's methodology, one his reception, one his logic, one relationships to other theories of capital accumulation, and one Weber's broader work on the economy and religion. The edition also includes a chronology and selected bibliography for Weber.<br /><br />For an affordable, reasonably sized paperback, the editors have done an excellent job.<br /></span>
