    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3094731306" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3094731306" />
    <a title="William Bies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/104781119-william-bies"><img alt="William Bies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641096050p2/104781119.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3094731306?book_show_action=true">Dec 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William Bies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William Bies" href="/user/show/104781119-william-bies">William Bies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9783406511332" href="/book/show/3983417-die-protestantische-ethik-und-der-geist-des-kapitalismus">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3094731306" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13190512608010972808">Max Weber’s thesis on the Protestant ethic and the spirit of capitalism has been a locus classicus of the sociological debate for well over a century now, but it will come as little wonder that it is frequently misunderstood by those who pay insufficient attention to his original texts. This new complete edition offers not just the original essays of 1904-1906, but also Weber’s extensive annotations and replies to his critics added to the reprinting of 1920 as well as a modern introduction by Di</span>
  <span id="freeText13190512608010972808" style="display:none">Max Weber’s thesis on the Protestant ethic and the spirit of capitalism has been a locus classicus of the sociological debate for well over a century now, but it will come as little wonder that it is frequently misunderstood by those who pay insufficient attention to his original texts. This new complete edition offers not just the original essays of 1904-1906, but also Weber’s extensive annotations and replies to his critics added to the reprinting of 1920 as well as a modern introduction by Dirk Kaesler. Kaesler helpfully situates the present work on the Protestant ethic within the context of Weber’s larger sociology of religion, which includes studies of the positions taken by the world religions on questions of the economy and ethics. As Weber himself makes clear, a capitalist ethos of some sort or other has existed in many times and places; his particular interest in Protestantism stems not from a belief that it, uniquely, was responsible for the rise of capitalism in the West, but from the specific features of its ethics, which not only were well suited to play an auxiliary role in promoting capitalist enterprise but also can be connected with the nature of modernity as such, under the rubric of the ‘rationalization of all domains of life’. For to understand this latter is Weber’s primary concern, as readers who are familiar with his other work on bureaucratization in modern nation-states will know.<br /><br />To the work itself: Weber, as befits the sociologist, adopts a nondogmatic approach to his subject. His concern is not with theological doctrine per se but with the effect it exerts on lifestyles in a society in which adherents of the religious confession in question play a predominant culture-forming role. Clearly, the Reformation represents a departure from medieval society, the more so under Calvin and his sectarian successors than under Luther himself. Nonetheless, the way it worked itself out sociologically is not necessarily so transparent. Weber leads off with statistics on the disproportionately Protestant confessional makeup of the management class versus the relatively more Catholic artisan class in Germany of his day, around 1900, which serve to confirm what many long suspected but which, for him, merely establish a terminus ad quem. From Weber’s perspective, the reason for an outcome such as this is that Protestants tend to strive to work their way into upper management, where they can exert a controlling influence on the direction taken by the firm and on capital formation, while the ethic among Catholics centers more on achieving mastery of artisanal technique and, so it appears, is willing to leave the guidance of the firm largely to others. What interests Weber is why things turned out this way, and, with good reason, he surmises that the explanation is to be sought in their differing religious outlooks, rooted in theological doctrine.<br /><br />First, what is the supposed ‘spirit of capitalism’? Weber’s derives this from an extensive quotation from Benjamin Franklin, who, as an American, represents for Weber at its most advanced a view of life dominated by business, to the exclusion of other cultural occupations such as art or religious meditation. Now, in his advice to young professionals on how to get ahead, Franklin is perhaps the first to underline with utmost clarity that ‘time is money’. Time spent on entertainment or other diversions is wasted in the sense that it could be better applied to economic interests. Money spent on consumer goods is nothing but a lost investment. Not only this, ‘credit is money’; i.e., a reputation for a stern work ethic, punctuality, justice in all one’s dealings etc. serves a man well because people will want to do business with a man such as this. Hence, the maxim ‘honesty is the best policy’ should be observed on strictly pragmatic grounds. What Weber sees behind all of Franklin’s expressions of this sort is a view of life according to which professional success is the alpha and omega of morality.<br /><br />Now, Franklin was hardly a religious man, but, for Weber, his secular view of life ultimately rests upon a religious foundation, viz., the concept of professional calling, what is distinctive to modern capitalist society in the West and is not found in other world cultures, no matter how much economic activity they may have engaged in that could be described in a loose sense as capitalist. In scripture, a calling – literally – comes directly from God or his prophetic representatives and commits one to lifelong service of strictly religious ideals. How could the modern worldly view of a professional calling have descended from such antecedents? This gets us to the heart of Weber’s argument.<br /><br />The emergence of the capitalist spirit represents for Weber an important moment in the overall process of rationalization of life. Protestantism comes into historical consideration in so far as it contributes to the rise of a purely rationalistic view of life, which encompasses not just legal reforms to establish the right to private property but – what is most important – the functionalization of one’s entire life itself to the furtherance of the purpose of professional success.<br /><br />Luther’s abolition of the Catholic distinction between precepts (rules binding on everyone) and counsels (as in the three evangelical counsels of poverty, chastity and obedience which undergird the properly religious life and are not binding on everyone) gave rise to the centrality of the Protestant understanding of calling also in a worldly sense, for now the layman could please God by fulfilling his innerworldly duty, not just by renouncing the world and becoming a monk. We have not yet arrived at the ‘capitalist spirit’ but Luther’s disdain for contemplation does set the stage for it. All along, the Catholic view had been that work is a duty that befalls us in consequence of original sin and that there would be no duty to work, if we could survive without it. Adam in Paradise was not under the necessity to work but was free to contemplate the heavenly realities. But, for Luther, one’s <i>innerworldly</i> profession, not contemplation, is the <i>sole</i> manner in which one can be pleasing to God.<br /><br />The second major part, on the professional ethic of ascetical Protestantism, spells out the development that ensues from Luther’s starting point. Here is where Weber deploys his theological guns. In short: the Calvinistic doctrine of double predestination removes the possibility on the part of the individual of seeking relief through periodic confession of his sins to the priest and reception of priestly absolution in the sacrament. How then can one have any confidence that one belongs to the elect? The Protestants revived the Old Testament criterion of wealth as a sign of God’s favor. Now this may seem idle, from a sociological point of view, but Weber’s brilliant insight is to delve into the psychology of the self that such a theological position entails. For, if professional success is the sign by which I can recognize God’s favor, in order to secure my confidence in his favor I must regulate my entire life according to the virtues that will promote said professional success. Here is Weber’s crucial observation: this means that Protestant asceticism takes, not the form of an episodic renewal of grace such as is possible for the Catholic through the sacrament of penance, but a thoroughgoing rationalized form of life, governed at every juncture by what is necessary to further professional success. Hence, the virtues of sobriety, responsibility, justice, honesty, hard work, time management, temperance and avoidance of the diversion of dissipation, entertainment and consumption of luxury goods. In other words, one has to take a <i>methodical</i> view of one’s entire life and character, rather than fall back on an occasional repentance. <br /><br />With this, we’ve gotten to the crux of Weber’s argument, for from here it is evident that, when such a perspective on life is applied in commercial countries such as the Netherlands or the Huguenots in France, the result will be a powerful stimulus to capitalist development, which, as we know, depends on reinvestment of profits and long-term planning, rather than the shortsighted diversion of surplus profits into the acquisition of unnecessary property or other cultural goods. Let us leave it to the interested reader to follow how Weber spells out, in the remainder of this part and in his following essay on sectarianism, the economic and social consequences of innerworldly Protestant asceticism. Just two remarks: 1) the contrast with the medieval guilds: the guilds were concerned with regulating the conditions of competition among colleagues, hence contributed to civic virtues and a sense of social justice, while Protestants, especially sectarians (Puritans, Baptists, Quakers, Pietists etc.), were individualistically oriented and were primarily concerned with rationalizing their conduct of life in order to promote the chances of their coreligionists within the larger society, hence the relative absence of a social-justice tradition, which must take its wellsprings from a sense of the common good. 2) The contrast between medieval monkish asceticism with rational Protestant innerworldly asceticism: the latter rejects irrational ascetical methods, contemplation and withdrawal from the world. More deeply: the monks saw their ascetical practice as a real ground of the expectation of future blessedness while Protestants saw theirs as merely a means by which to recognize their elect status.<br /><br />The evangelical Protestants in present-day Latin America view their church membership in crassly functional terms as a credential in the world of work, and even list it on their business cards. Who says one can’t serve both God and Mammon at the same time? For going on two generations, evangelical Protestantism has been eating away at the Church in Latin America like a cancer, converting it into a liturgical wasteland in which the Eucharist is no longer celebrated and rich spiritual traditions going back to the apostles are consigned to oblivion, rather as, out of sheer greed, Brazilian farmers in the Amazon basin are now zealously committed to the project of reverse-terraforming the rainforest into a denuded Martian desert. There can be no doubt that it is preferentially the ‘better’ and more ‘respectable’ sort who convert to Protestantism, while it is predominantly those who are poorer (both in spirit and in material terms) and less well educated who remain loyal to the age-old faith (as it probably was in the old days of Luther, Calvin and Zwingli, as well). A deep religious culture is being replaced by that superficial Americanism, the ‘prosperity gospel’, which, it should go without saying, though understandable and all too human, is utterly antithetical to the message of the New Testament. Strictly speaking, Protestants, whether in America or in Europe, do not have culture in the sense that Roman Catholics and the eastern Orthodox do.<br /><br />The lesson of Weber: it was ever thus. He recounts his experiences at a baptism ceremony held by revivalist Baptists in a river in North Carolina. His traveling companion remarked: ‘Mr. X? Why, of course!’ It turns out that X was looking to open a bank and to be admitted to baptism was a shrewd business move, not just to garner support of coreligionists but because, among all Protestant sects, the Baptists enjoyed the reputation of being the most stringent and thorough in vetting their candidates for a good moral character. X’s future customers could be pretty well sure that he never drank to excess, went carousing, committed adultery, failed to pay his bills promptly etc.<br /><br />The dismal conclusion: in Germany of Weber’s time the conventional view of Puritanism was that it consists in nothing but self-righteous hypocrisy. Weber the sociologist withholds a value judgment on the religious phenomena he exposes, but it would be hard to gainsay the lesson implicit in Weber’s writings. For this reviewer, the most salient theological point to emerge from this essay on the Protestant ethic is that, at least in the way it worked itself out historically, Protestantism represents, in effect, a revival of the Donatist heresy from the fifth century, which so exercised Augustine. For certainly, the Protestant sectarian logic of denominational splintering is grounded upon the deep-seated conviction that one is better than the others, as far as moral observance goes, the very same thing that motivated the Donatists, who prided themselves on having resisted Diocletian’s persecution and despised those who, out of weakness, fell away to the point that they could not be readmitted to church membership. What actuates the Protestants’ strict legalistic policy of exclusion from eucharistic fellowship is a horror at having to associate with known, flagrant sinners. It seems to be iron-clad logic, although Weber does not remark upon it, that, once the sacrament of penance and reconciliation has been eliminated, sin, or at least serious sin after baptism, becomes virtually unforgivable, just the opposite of what Jesus tells us (Matthew 18:22). In the gospels, Jesus has the temerity to dine with tax collectors, prostitutes and sinners; the Protestants, most especially the sectarians, have been bound and determined to rectify Jesus’ error. One can well suppose that, when the Eucharist has been deprived of its real presence, when its sacramental character as a thanksgiving to God has been forgotten, what remains of communion is nothing but a powerful instrument of social control, to be wielded in a fashion Pharisaical to the utmost.<br /><br />Some brief final remarks. The Antikritik, in which Weber responds to his critics, covers little new ground. Weber is evidently just too superior to his critics, who are guilty of elementary misreadings that anyone who reads the original texts should know better than; this causes one to wonder whether German academics during the 19th to early 20th century really were all they are cracked up to be. Lastly, the religious phenomena under Weber’s microscope pertain to the early modern period in Europe and America. In places, Weber recognizes that the situation has changed radically now that scarcely anyone (in Europe at least) is a serious religious believer anymore. How does the capitalist spirit change upon secularization, when the purely religious motive of solicitude for one’s salvation is withdrawn? Liberal Protestantism was already at its zenith in Weber’s time. One wishes Weber could have entered into a treatment of what happens to the moral or economic organization of society once its religious roots fall into a process of terminal dissolution, but he probably feels this to be beyond his remit. The most one can gather from scattered remarks is that he sees America as a bellwether of what is likely to come (about which he harbors rather dismissive judgments).</span>
  <a data-text-id="13190512608010972808" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


