  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2633028235" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2633028235" />
    <a title="Ian Caveny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21216968-ian-caveny"><img alt="Ian Caveny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1583164141p2/21216968.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2633028235?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ian Caveny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ian Caveny" href="/user/show/21216968-ian-caveny">Ian Caveny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140439212" href="/book/show/195070.The_Protestant_Ethic_and_the_Spirit_of_Capitalism_and_Other_Writings">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21216968-ian-caveny?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21216968-ian-caveny?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2633028235" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3939145888244295210">It&apos;s a classic argument: the Calvinists of the 17th century were so preoccupied with proving their salvific status that they put their focus into hard work and labor, developing a work ethic that has stayed with us even when its original heaven-or-hell anxiety has faded away. However we might view or understand Max Weber now, one hundred years later, credit is due him on a number of accounts: 1) he laid the foundations for sociology as a field of study; and 2) he was one of the earliest modern s</span>
  <span id="freeText3939145888244295210" style="display:none">It's a classic argument: the Calvinists of the 17th century were so preoccupied with proving their salvific status that they put their focus into hard work and labor, developing a work ethic that has stayed with us even when its original heaven-or-hell anxiety has faded away. However we might view or understand Max Weber now, one hundred years later, credit is due him on a number of accounts: 1) he laid the foundations for sociology as a field of study; and 2) he was one of the earliest modern scholars to take the <i>practical outcomes</i> of religious beliefs seriously.<br /><br />There are numerous misunderstandings regarding his thesis that reading it helps clear up: for one, Weber is not discussing the Calvinism of John Calvin. For him, the doctrines of the "Protestant ethic" are less important than the mindsets of the common people under certain doctrinal systems, and in his view it is the Puritan, Anabaptist, Baptist, and Methodist develops (and responses) to Scholastic Calvinism that are most significant. He does this to great effect when quoting Richard Baxter on work, drawing a line of continuity from Baxter's formal teachings and the lifestyles of the everyday Puritan under his leadership.<br /><br />Another common misunderstanding is that Weber's thesis is preoccupied with predestination. This was a more minor point than I had expected it to be, from what others had told me about the book. For Weber, the development of a "capitalist spirit" comes not directly from predestination but from the "ascetic way-of-life" that comes with predestination's counterpart: sanctification. In Lutheranism, and even in old-school Anglicanism, the "church" is a mixed entity including both the "Church visible" and "Church invisible." We hear this language today in Presbyterian circles especially (some of whom are more direct inheritors of the Calvinist legacy than the "Calvinists" Weber discusses; the shifting nature of terms in religious discourse is part of what makes Weber easy to misunderstand!). But for Baptists, for instance, the "church" is those who are gathered together with <i>declared allegiance and demonstrated life-change</i>, who have been baptized into the church and, thus, gain their membership. From <i>this practice</i>, social-economic standards begin to develop creating certain work-ethic pressures.<br /><br />These common misunderstandings of Weber aside, the central thread of his argument is sound. But it is defended and deployed in a surprisingly haphazard fashion. The man suffers from something many writers experience: the full picture in the head without the ability to explain it adequately for an audience. It is no surprise that Weber encounter terse rejoinders from certain academic crowds and that he responds with such vitriol (these responses are included in the Penguin edition). It is a wonder that anyone really understood his argument in the first place!<br /><br />The most useful chunk is near the end of the "The Protestant Ethic...," in which he begins to cite actual Puritans for his case. There the case is pretty clear: an ascetic way-of-life partnered with a valuation of making money minus an intention to spend that money on pleasure. Richard Baxter and John Bunyan both exemplify this kind of ethics. I feel this part of his argument is extraordinary and worth re-visiting, especially as it pertains to the ethics of Baptist and (for us) Evangelical churches. There is a contemporary analysis waiting to be explored here.<br /><br />But the threads that are most important for Weber to make his point are not explicated with much specificity. I disagree with H. Karl Fischer, who accused Weber of Hegelianism. He sure sounds like an idealist at times, but the weight of his argument is on concrete activity. Nevertheless, Weber's methodology leaves much to be desired. A thorough exegesis of period Calvinists from the beginning with a discussion on the theological relationship between their views on work and their views on salvation would have been a far better place to begin, and would have resulted in a more interesting argument.<br /><br />As it stands, however, "The Protestant Ethic" is nevertheless a landmark text in scholarly work. And there is still much truth to the sense that there is some relationship between "ascetic" churches (e.g. Puritan and Baptist) and the "spirit" of capitalism. But what is that precise relationship? who influences who? Weber, unfortunately, does not put together all we need to make those kinds of conclusions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3939145888244295210" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

