<div id="review_1481614109" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1481614109" />
    <a title="Matthew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/186871-matthew"><img alt="Matthew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1184350333p2/186871.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1481614109?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew" href="/user/show/186871-matthew">Matthew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/186871-matthew?shelf=worldview">worldview</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/186871-matthew?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1481614109" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15021021388028024596">Weber seems like an intelligent fellow, yet the book is filled with misrepresentations of Christianity, particularly Calvinism, and some of its adherents. The premise is very interesting: is there something inherent in Protestant theology that gives rise to pure capitalism? Weber says yes, but comes to a conclusion that it is owed to a &quot;worldly asceticism&quot; which brought Christians out of the monasteries and made them veracious savers. This may be in part true (monks aren&apos;t known to be players in</span>
  <span id="freeText15021021388028024596" style="display:none">Weber seems like an intelligent fellow, yet the book is filled with misrepresentations of Christianity, particularly Calvinism, and some of its adherents. The premise is very interesting: is there something inherent in Protestant theology that gives rise to pure capitalism? Weber says yes, but comes to a conclusion that it is owed to a "worldly asceticism" which brought Christians out of the monasteries and made them veracious savers. This may be in part true (monks aren't known to be players in the economic system), but he ignores the development of the doctrine of vocation and the conviction that the Christian is to "work as unto the Lord."<br /><br />His historical analysis leads him to his conclusion but it is based on anecdotal observance with no statistical or other provable data. Knowing something of Calvinist doctrine I was disappointed at the rampant misrepresentation of Calvinists as terrified God-pleasers eager to demonstrate their elect status by endless good works. In fact, he comments that strict Calvinists are basically moralists who adhere to an "awful doctrine" of predestination...but I digress.<br /><br />Weber sees this brand of Protestantism as basically a social movement (in regards to economics), held to by faithful practitioners, but misses the mark on their true motivation. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15021021388028024596" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


